{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}} {{Use British English|date=August 2015}} [[File:Staging the World catalogue cover.jpg|thumb|right|The exhibition's catalogue.]] '''Shakespeare: Staging the World''' was an exhibition at the [[British Museum]] about the world of Shakespeare, showing the way that he portrayed the world in his plays and related it to the events and politics of contemporary London. It was produced as part of the [[World Shakespeare Festival]] and ran from 19 July to 25 November 2012.
==Reception== The exhibition was well received by the critics and press. [[Katherine Duncan-Jones]] wrote, "...the exhibition has something for everyone, and deserves more than one visit."<ref>{{citation |title=The world Shakespeare festival – authentic or eccentric? |author=Katherine Duncan-Jones |date=8 August 2012 |journal=[[Times Literary Supplement]] |url=http://www.the-tls.co.uk/tls/public/article1099143.ece}}</ref> [[Michael Billington (critic)|Michael Billington]] wrote, "What I like about the exhibition is that so many of the artefacts, including paintings, maps, globes, domestic objects and military weapons, relate to specific images in Shakespeare's plays. ... It's a brilliant exhibition ...".<ref>{{citation | url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2012/jul/19/shakespeare-staging-the-world-review |title=Shakespeare: Staging the World – review |journal=[[The Guardian]] |author=Michael Billington |date=19 July 2012}}</ref>
The book accompanying the exhibition, by the Shakespeare scholar [[Jonathan Bate]] and [[Dora Thornton]], Renaissance curator at the museum, was especially praised. Richard Dorment, theatre critic of the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', wrote, "The catalogue by Bate and Thornton is well worth reading for its own sake, and once you start you won’t be able to stop."<ref>{{citation | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/william-shakespeare/9404131/Shakespeare-Staging-the-World-review.html |title=Shakespeare: Staging the World, review |journal=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | author=Richard Dorment |date=16 Jul 2012}}</ref> [[Brian Sewell]] wrote, "... the catalogue should be in every school library in the land. ... every student of English literature should have his own copy and that the book should never go out of print."<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/arts/visual-arts/brian-sewell-on-shakespeare-staging-the-world-british-museum-7978471.html |title=Brian Sewell on Shakespeare: Staging the World, British Museum |journal=[[Evening Standard]] |date=26 July 2012 |author=Brian Sewell}}</ref>
==Objects== The objects exhibited included: the [[Blacas Cameo]], the [[Dunstable Swan Jewel]], [[Royal Gold Cup]], [[Brooch of Lorn]], and the [[Quentin Metsys the Younger|Metsys]] Siena [[Portraiture of Elizabeth I of England#The Virgin Queen|''Sieve Portrait of Elizabeth I'']].
