'''Shecky's Media, Inc.''' is an American event promoter and city guide publisher.

[[Manhattan]] entrepreneur Chris Hoffman grew Shecky's into a multi-million dollar women-centric media company featuring his Girls' Night Out events that were held in 12 cities across the U.S. Over the years, Hoffman continued to expand Shecky’s Girls’ Night Out,<ref>Lerner, Dana. [http://journalism.nyu.edu/pubzone/livewire/archived/fashionistas_flock_to_sheckys/ "Fashionistas Flock to Shecky's Girls Night Out"], ''NYU LiveWire'' {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070403145830/http://journalism.nyu.edu/pubzone/livewire/archived/fashionistas_flock_to_sheckys/ |date=2007-04-03 }}</ref> and Beauty Week,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.savvysocialite.com/2007/05/08/sheckys-girls-night-out/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-06-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070513153734/http://www.savvysocialite.com/2007/05/08/sheckys-girls-night-out/ |archivedate=2007-05-13 }}</ref> attracting sponsors looking to advertise to the Shecky’s audience. The New York event is held in Manhattan's landmark [[Puck Building]].

In 2006, Shecky's opened a fashion boutique in Manhattan's Lower East Side named Shecky's Shop.<ref>Zappia, Corrina. [http://www.villagevoice.com/news/sheckys-vs-girlshop-6399906 " Shecky's vs. Girlshop"], ''The Village Voice'', March 3, 2006, Retrieved October 15, 2016.</ref> Shecky's Shop closed in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sheckysshop.com/home2.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-06-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809013427/http://sheckysshop.com/home2.html |archivedate=2007-08-09 }}</ref>

